The dry, stark, hard-edged realism of everyday life, almost documentary-like in style (handheld camerawork, absence of non-diegetic music, often non-professional actors), is the hallmark the Dardenne brothers stubbornly cling to regardless of the sociological subject at hand. And no, it&#39;s not always the optimal choice. In this film, for instance, some emotions feel authentic while others come across as mechanical and contrived. &quot;It&#39;s precisely on such a fault line between genuine inspiration and worn-out convention that &#39;Jeunes Mères&#39; positions itself, likely lauded on the Croisette well beyond its actual merits&quot; (Raffaele Meale), complete with &quot;dramaturgical lapses and an energy that gradually dissipates, rendering Cannes&#39; Best Screenplay prize baffling&quot; (Davide Turrini). The very recent Censis report confirms that fewer than three couples out of ten now have children (29.2%), and that the average age of mothers at the birth of their first child has risen to 31.9 years: realities that barely penetrate the ivory tower in which cinema has shut itself away in France as in Belgium or, conversely, the supposed global panacea of a quintet of fifteen-year-old girls and not a single abortion? Alessandra De Luca (&quot;Avvenire&quot;) and Franco Lorusso (&quot;L&#39;Osservatore Romano&quot;) applaud thunderously.</div><!----></div><!--[--><div class="review-footer review-footer--user movie-review-footer" data-v-ab61ed06 data-v-cfb925ca data-v-d4a3ca9a><!--[--><!--]--><!----><span class="review-action-button review-report-link" data-v-d4a3ca9a data-v-c45629df data-v-5fd1ab98><!--[--><svg class="review-report-link__icon" data-v-c45629df><title>report-review</title><use href="#flag"></use></svg><!--]--> Report <!--[--><!--]--></span><!--[--><!--]--></div><!--]--></div><!--[--><!--]--><!--]--><!--]--></div><!--[--><a href="/movie/young-mothers/user-reviews/" data-slot="base" class="font-medium aria-disabled:cursor-not-allowed aria-disable